<hl>
<seg id=1> Supporting Countries: Japan, Australia, New Zealand and South Korea. America had no other choice </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> Tokyo Japan, Australia, New Zealand and South Korea, etc. supported the "Action of Desert Fox", and they said that America had no other choice. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> Japanese Prime Minister Koizumi expressed that he supported the air raid action, and called on Baghdad to accept weapon inspection without preconditions. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Koizumi made announcements that after restoration of weapon inspection, Iraq "didn't give enough "cooperation. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> "In view of the situation in the past, my country supports American and British action." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> South Korea also supported the united air raid action of America and Britain. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> Australian Prime Minister Howard said that after reading the report by Leader of the Weapon Inspection Delegation of the United Nations Bartler, he believed that America and Britain launched the attack because they had no other choice. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> France and Germany expressed their regret and sadness. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> Prime Minister of New Zealand made special announcements that the whole world would not allow Hussain to continue going against the decision of the United States any more. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> In addition, France showed their regret for American and British action. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=11> The  French Ministry of Foreign Affairs said that it's a really sad result since the leaders of Iraq had refused to cooperate with the United Nations. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> Germany felt sad about the military action. A spokesman for the government pointed out that Germany once warned Iraq that the whole world wouldn't allow Iraq to continue going against the decision of the United States without any action. </seg>
</p>
